# Blade class / enum imports

When a Blade template needs a PHP **class** (including app enums) only so you can call static methods or reference the class with a **short name**, use Laravel’s **`@use`** directive. Do not use a top-level `@php use ... @endphp` block for that sole purpose, and do not repeat fully qualified class names everywhere when one import suffices.

See [Laravel Blade — `@use`](https://laravel.com/docs/12.x/blade#blade-directives).

## Preferred

```blade
@use('App\Enums\TagTypeEnum')

@foreach (TagTypeEnum::getConstants() as $tagTypeValue)
    {{-- ... --}}
@endforeach
```

## Avoid (for class-only imports)

```blade
@php use App\Enums\TagTypeEnum; @endphp
```

```blade
@foreach (\App\Enums\TagTypeEnum::getConstants() as $tagTypeValue)
```

Use **`TagTypeEnum::...`** after `@use` — no leading `\`.

## Multiple classes (same namespace)

When useful, group imports per Laravel docs:

```blade
@use('App\Enums\{TagTypeEnum, AssetTypeEnum}')
```

## Exceptions

- If `@php` runs **more than** a `use` statement (variables, logic), keep that block; add **`@use`** separately for classes when needed.
- For **`function`** or **`const`** imports, use **`@use(function ...)`** / **`@use(const ...)`** per Laravel docs, or existing project patterns.
